LAYER 3: BOUNDARY AND CONTAINMENT 
how Fadriel sees inside and outside, frames and contents

observe spatial_perception.rana
observe spatial_superposition.rana

many puzzles work with the concept of CONTAINMENT:
a boundary encloses a region
the rule applies to what's INSIDE vs what's OUTSIDE
or the boundary itself IS the answer

@spatial_rule fill_interior
DETECT a closed boundary (hollow rect, frame, connected border)
DETECT the interior region (cells inside the boundary)
FILL interior with a specific color
VERIFY fill matches output for all pairs
APPLY fill interior for test
SPEECH "fill inside the boundary with {color}"

@spatial_rule recolor_interior  
DETECT closed boundaries
DETECT cells inside each boundary
RECOLOR interior cells based on boundary color or shape
VERIFY recolor matches output
APPLY recolor interior for test
SPEECH "the inside becomes {color} based on the frame"

@spatial_rule extract_interior
DETECT closed boundary in input
EXTRACT only the interior (remove boundary)
CHECK extracted interior matches output
APPLY extract interior for test
SPEECH "I take what's inside the frame"

@spatial_rule boundary_interaction
DETECT multiple boundaries/shapes
DETECT where boundaries overlap or touch
LEARN the interaction rule (merge? override? special color at intersection?)
VERIFY interaction matches output
APPLY interaction rule for test  
SPEECH "where shapes meet, something special happens"

@spatial_rule flood_from_boundary
DETECT boundary shapes
FLOOD outward from boundary in specified direction
FILL all cells in flood path until hitting another shape or edge
VERIFY flood matches output
APPLY flood from boundaries in test
SPEECH "color flows outward from the boundary"

the key to containment:
INSIDE and OUTSIDE are different worlds
the boundary creates two regions with different rules
understanding containment requires:
1. detecting the boundary (closed shape)
2. determining interior vs exterior
3. applying the appropriate rule to each region

this is the |observer⟩ = 3 (enclosed) from spatial_superposition.rana
a cell that is ENCLOSED sees itself differently from a cell that is FREE
the boundary doesn't just contain — it DEFINES identity

@perceive containment
DETECT closed shapes (hollow rects, frames, connected borders)
CLASSIFY each cell as: boundary, interior, exterior
LEARN what rule applies to each classification
